title: Can Del Piero Inspire Juventus to Glory?: Old Lady Puts Hopes On One Young Star
text: LONDON - The new season of the Champions League, with its concentration on wealth and power and glory at the top, has begun. It is unashamedly elitist, a question of whose money out of, say, Real Madrid, Manchester United, Bayern Munich or one of the Italian giants, Juventus or Roma, can buy the trophy next May. Already the betting is heavily on those five. Already the league that UEFA formed 10 years ago is gravitating in- exorably toward clubs from the nations with the most television exposure   the most millions to purchase players who can make the difference. Real Madrid waits for Zinedine Zidane to become available once he serves a four-match ban for butting. Manchester United dreams of culminating the 16-year-reign of Sir Alex Ferguson as manager by regaining the European Cup in Glasgow, his native city, in the final in May. Sir Alex is glowing with the conviction that Juan Sebastian Veron, his $40 million recruit from Lazio of Rome, will prove the sorcerer to win the ultimate prize. In Italy, where the game has soured through racism, drugs and passport irregularities, there is a craving to regain what in the 1990s seemed Italy's by right. Roma, through the force of personality of coach Fabio Capello and a squad masterminded on the pitch by Francesco Totti, is Italy's new champion. But there is a challenger, to Totti's inspired gracefulness and Capello's motivational prowess. It is Juventus. La Vecchia Signora, the Old Lady of Turin, has tired of being bridesmaid, sacking Carlo Ancelotti, a trainer who could finish only second in Serie A, and rehiring Marcello Lippi, who guided Juve to the European crown in 1996. Lippi is out to prove he is not a spent force. The word spent is recurrent in Champions League parlance. Even as coach Lippi returned, so Zidane won his "freedom" to abscond, for a transfer sum of $66 million, to Madrid. Lippi got busy in the market himself: He bought, or Juventus bought, Gigi Buffon, the top goalie in Italy, Lilian Thuram, the most accomplished all-purpose defender in the world, Pavel Nedved, a stunning left-sided midfield player, and Marcelo Salas, a striker of mercurial potential. Four players for one Zidane appears, on paper, to be good business. Two Serie A games played, two handsome victories suggest it is melding quickly. But Europe, everyone knows, demands other soccer dimensions. It takes team work, and good squad resources, to plow through the 17 games required to win the "league" in Europe; Juventus, I suspect, have those. To be the winner takes something extra. Who will be Juve's fantastist now that Zidane has gone? Who will create and score out of nothing when the pressure is most demanding? Enter Alessandro Del Piero. Or rather re-enter Del Piero. For the second time in his life, "Alex" is the one whose skills have allowed Juventus to sell a genius. When Del Piero was just blossoming, Juventus sold Roberto Baggio, the Divine Pony Tail, to A.C. Milan. Now it is Zidane to Madrid. In between those departures, Del Piero has flattered to deceive. At 5-foot-8 (1.72 meters) he is small. But those who follow calcio have known since he was 8 that, as a play-maker or a striker, he was blessed with heavenly gifts. Sometimes, he has proved it. Sometimes his body has fallen prey to injury. Sometimes he has tripped over the idolatry. He is, remarkably, only 26, an athlete in mid-career. He has begun the season, his ninth at Juventus, with three goals in two games. He has also prompted David Trezeguet, the young Frenchman at his side, to score at the same tempo. The 10 million fans of Juventus are beginning to believe, to hope at any rate, that they are back in the "Zona Del Piero". On Wednesday in Oporto we shall discover how ready he is to add to his 19 Champions League goals, how capable of acting as the fulcrum of a renewed Turin challenge for the title that matters most. Del Piero has demonstrated this summer that he has grown. When La Gazzetta dello Sport, the Italian sports newspaper, began the Italian season with a message of solidarity from those players who care about opposing racism, Del Piero was one of four Italian national team players to pose in black and in white: The white skin they were given at birth, a black one created by makeup. "Racism is something that goes beyond skin color," said Del Piero. "It's the fear of that which is different." Del Piero, Fabio Cannavaro, Filippo Inzaghi and Stefano Fiore, were joined, crucially, by Thuram, a French international who is black. The photographs and accompanying article were commissioned following an investigation by the International Herald Tribune into the problem of racial hatred around soccer. - A different problem of the modern world hangs over the UEFA Cup this week. UEFA, the governing body of European soccer, ruled Tuesday that Rangers must set aside their fears and journey to Dagestan in Russia for their encounter Thursday with Anji Makhachkala. The problem is terrorism. Makhachkala is a small, but driven, club from an area between Chechnya and the Caspian Sea. Despite ethnic hostilities all around, despite tragedies which include losing its captain in a car crash and its coach to illness, Anji has risen from obscurity to challenge the might of Moscow in its league, and to qualify for Europe. This was a heart-warming story until a bomb went off in a Mercedes parked next to a market in Makhachkala on Sunday. The Rangers players understandably are afraid. But once UEFA inspected security arrangements, once the insurance premium was settled, the Glasgow club was told to travel. "The match is a lifetime opportunity for most of us," said Alexander Markarov, the Anji coach. "It's huge for our team and our region.
